        g: '06477000', avg: 800, histFlow: 720, mx: 395, my: 135, abbr: 'SD',
        desc: "The longest unnavigable river in America — or so the old joke goes. The James meanders 710 miles from North Dakota to the Missouri, making it one of the longest tributaries in the country. In reality, the James is navigable for much of its length and offers classic Great Plains prairie paddling through endless grassland.",
        desig: 'James River Water Trail candidate',
        secs: ['Aberdeen to Huron — 120 mi, upper James, slow prairie meanders', 'Huron to Mitchell — 100 mi, middle James, wider channel', 'Mitchell to Yankton — 150 mi, lower James, deeper and faster to the Missouri'],
        history: [
          { era: 'native', entries: [{ yr: 'Pre-contact', title: 'Dakota Sioux — James River Valley', text: "The James River valley was central Dakota (Eastern Sioux) territory. The river's gentle flow and fertile bottomlands supported semi-permanent villages along its length. The Dakota name for the river emphasized its slow, winding character through the vast prairie.", src: 'South Dakota State Historical Society; Yankton Sioux Tribe' }] },
          { era: 'logging', entries: [{ yr: '1880s', title: 'Great Dakota Boom — Railroad and Settlement', text: "The 'Great Dakota Boom' of the 1880s brought railroads and thousands of homesteaders to the James River valley. Towns like Aberdeen, Huron, and Mitchell sprang up along the river, transforming the prairie into one of America's most productive agricultural regions.", src: 'South Dakota State Historical Society' }] },
        ],
